So, we find the total number of minimally intersecting set subsets $\binom{7}{1} \cdot \binom{6}{1} \cdot \binom{5}{1}$ right here as we are considering each subset three times. So, this must be our total number for the minimally intersecting set $N = \binom{7}{1} \cdot \binom{6}{1} \cdot \binom{5}{1}$. Formally, what we did was found it was best to categorize everything by the elements in the sets as stated in the first section. Therefore, each of the $7$ elements are considered into $3$ different sets with $1$ intersection between two of the three sets. So, we consider the elements into pairs and remove repeating elements out of all of the elements. Then, we can do it again for all the elements in the set to create a new set of which is independent of the other two. Now, this is $n = 7$ and the total elements for the set is our $k = 3$ because each set $A,B,C$ is independent of each element strided it with all of the elements out of the $7$ but without doing it again another time within each of the three intersections. Multiplying these to total sums it up to give us the equation $n \cdot \binom{k}{2} \cdot k$. Since $n,k$ is our $n=7,k=3$ this would be the answer if we did not take into consideration that we are dividing it by $1000$ at the end. Therefore, the number is $7 \choose 2$ $\cdot 3^3 = <343>$ \end{ think}
